2 Background and Related Work
2.1 EO Satellite Scheduling
The EO scheduling problem was formally posed by Bensana et al. [5] and defined comprehensively by Lemaître et al. [6] for the French Pléiades programme. The goal is to maximise total observation profit subject to visibility windows, transition constraints (minimum rotation and stabilization time between observations), and onboard resource limits (memory, energy). Agile satellites can adjust their attitude along three axes, extending observation windows but introducing sequence-dependent transition times that make the problem NP-hard [3].
Solution approaches span exact methods (branch-and-bound [7, 11], MILP [9], constraint programming [10, 12]), constructive and neighbourhood-search heuristics [6, 8, 19, 13, 14, 20], and deep reinforcement learning [15, 16, 17, 18]. Wang et al. [3] survey 62 papers over 20 years and Ferrari et al. [4] extend the coverage to 2024. Every method assumes a fully specified constraint model.
2.2 Optimization under Uncertain or Unknown Constraints
A related but distinct line of work addresses optimization when constraints are uncertain rather than unknown. Dong et al. [28] study cloud job scheduling where capacity constraints are stochastic and must be predicted from historical data. Their predict-then-optimise framework (CUC) handles distributional uncertainty but assumes the constraint structure is known and only the parameters are noisy. In contrast, our setting assumes prior knowledge of the constraint language but not of the hidden active model. That is, the learner knows the relevant families of constraints and a candidate basis, but must discover which constraints are actually justified, and at what parameter values, through binary feasibility queries.
2.3 Constraint Acquisition
Constraint acquisition learns a constraint satisfaction or optimisation model from data. Conacq [22] performs passive learning from labelled examples. QuAcq [23] introduced active acquisition via partial-assignment queries: given a negative example, its FindScope and FindC subroutines identify one exact constraint from the hidden model , maintaining the strong invariant . Extensions include multi-constraint acquisition [24], time-bounded query generation [25], structure exploitation [26] and qualitative constraint acquisition [31].
In its original formulation, Learn&Optimize [1] joins constraint acquisition with optimization, maintaining upper and lower bounds on the true optimum and allowing early termination when those bounds converge. Bessiere et al. [27] also study solving without an explicit model but via passive acquisition rather than interactive optimization. No prior work has applied constraint acquisition to EO scheduling.
