4.2 Conservative Constraint Acquisition (CCA)
CCA is a domain-specific procedure designed for the separation / capacity structure of EOSP-UC. It is not a general-purpose constraint acquisition algorithm: unlike QuAcq [23], it does not implement FindScope or FindC, and it does not generalise to arbitrary constraint languages. For other constraint families, QuAcq or its successors should be used.
The key idea is conservatism. When the oracle rejects a schedule, CCA refines the current constraint model using domain-specific partial queries and prunes dominated candidates from the basis. In an idealized setting this can be interpreted as learning constraints justified by the hidden model. In the present implementation we treat CCA operationally as a conservative model-refinement procedure rather than as a complete recovery algorithm for .
Procedure (Algorithm 2).
Given a rejected schedule :
-
1.
Pair querying. For each task pair whose current candidate separations are violated by , submit a two-task query and, if needed, binary-search over the sorted values in using window-consistent pair assignments. If a strongest justified gap is found, add to and prune all weaker separation candidates for that pair from .
-
2.
Capacity fallback. If no justified separation is found, learn the weakest violated capacity candidate, namely the smallest violated window width together with the largest still-violated capacity at that width.
After learning a constraint, prune by removing all dominated candidates. Here denotes the set of candidate separation values for pair currently present in .
4.3 Implementation Details
OptSol.
We implement OptSol using CP-SAT (Google OR-Tools) as a time-limited anytime solver. Each call is given a maximum time limit of cpsat_iter_t seconds (20 s in the reported experiments), although in practice CP-SAT often terminates much earlier when optimality is certified quickly. We use 4 parallel workers and a fixed random seed for reproducibility. CP-SAT returns the best feasible solution found within the time limit, along with a certificate of optimality if the search completes. When optimality is proved, the returned value coincides with the exact optimum of the current learned model, otherwise it should be read as the best value found under the current learned model within the time budget. Accordingly, the experimental “Opt()” curves are empirical CP-SAT values under , not certified upper bounds unless CP-SAT has proved optimality at that iteration.
FAO baseline.
FAO runs CCA for 100 queries, then solves the learned with CP-SAT. If the result violates , it is repaired by dropping lowest-priority tasks until oracle-feasible. Both FAO and L&O use CCA and receive the same oracle budget, so the comparison isolates the effect of interleaving acquisition with optimization.
